If an artifact is not found in the repository you specify, Maven will get it from Central, see the master POM definition at http://maven.apache.org/ref/3.0.4/maven-model-builder/super-pom.html

One way to override this &quot;base&quot; repository is to edit the Maven settings file `~/.m2/settings.xml` as the following, eg. to use the red-hat repo use:

    &lt;settings&gt;
      &lt;mirrors&gt;
        &lt;mirror&gt;
          &lt;id&gt;mirror-of-central&lt;/id&gt;
          &lt;mirrorOf&gt;central&lt;/mirrorOf&gt;
          &lt;url&gt;https://maven.repository.redhat.com/ga&lt;/url&gt;
        &lt;/mirror&gt;
      &lt;/mirrors&gt;
    &lt;/settings&gt;

and then call

    mvn dependency:get -Dartifact=org.springframework:spring-core:5.2.0.RELEASE

Note though, that this can fail if the given repo does not contain *all* required dependencies, including the Maven plugins.

---

**Edit**

If your final goal is to edit your company&#39;s builds so that the company repo is always used in place of maven central, using `&lt;mirror&gt;` as above should be the way to go.

